gland, United Kingdom","flatbury, Worcester Park, Surrey, England":"Worcester Park, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","flatbury, Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Coughton Fields, Warwickshire, England":"Coughton, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Thorckmorton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Throckmorton in Worcestershire, which is named with Old English <i>throc</i> ‘beam bridge’ + <i>mere</i> ‘pool’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’.","History: The Throckmorton family was powerful and influential in England in Tudor times, but has since almost died out there. American bearers of the name trace their descent from either John Throckmorton (1601–1684) of New England or Robert Throckmorton (1609–1663) of VA."],"variants":[{"name":"Throgmorton","meanings":["English: variant of   Throckmorton  ."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John de Thorckmorton was born in 1382, in Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas Throckmorton, Count de St. Pol, was 43 and his mother, Agnes Besford, was 32. He had at least 1 daughter with Eleanor de la Spine. He died on 12 April 1445, in Worcester Park, Surrey, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 63."},"et":{"1382–12 Apr 1445":"1382–12. aprill 1445","1382–1445":"1382–1445","1386–1463":"1386–1463","1386–1480":"1386–1480","1386–Female":"1386–Surnud","1387–1465":"1387–1465","1385–1467":"1385–1467","1424–1502":"1424–1502","1339–1412":"1339–1412","1350–1428":"1350–1428","1385":"1385","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","1480":"1480","1502":"1502","1424":"1424","1412":"1412